definition.value: A river in the States of Alabama and Florida, approximately 100 km long. The river forms part of the boundary between the two states along nearly its entire length and drains into the Gulf of Mexico. It rises in southeastern Alabama in Escambia County approximately 11 km NW of Atmore. It flows south approximately 8 km to latitude 31degN, south of which it forms the remainder of the Alabama/Florida border. It flows generally ESE in a winding course and enters the north end Perdido Bay on the Gulf of Mexico approximately 15 km west of Pensacola, Florida.
A river.
A river that begins at the south end of Lake Miccosukee in northwestern Jefferson County, Florida and flows 56 km through Leon and Wakulla counties into Apalachee Bay, an arm of the Gulf of Mexico.
A river in the southern United States which runs through Alabama and Florida. It empties into Blackwater Bay, an arm of Pensacola Bay.
A tidal river.

A north-flowing river in Volusia County, Florida, United States. The Tomoka rises in the forests near Daytona Beach at an elevation of 7.0 m. The river then flows north-northeast, passing through the cities Daytona Beach and Ormond Beach until it empties into the Halifax River. Near its mouth the river passes through the Tomoka Marsh Aquatic Preserve and Tomoka State Park.
A tidal river.
A tidal river. The river partly runs through the Jonathan Dickinson State Park. About 1 mile of it serves as the Palm Beach/Martin County border.

A river in South Florida, USA. The river originates in the Everglades and flows east. After passing through Fort Lauderdale, the river enters the Atlantic Ocean at Port Everglades cut. The river is entirely within Broward County and is composed from the junction of three main canals which originate in the Everglades, splitting off from the Miami Canal. They are the North New River Canal, which flows on the north side of State Road 84 / Interstate 595; the South New River Canal, which flows on the north side of Griffin Road and the south side of Orange Drive; and a canal which flows south of Sunrise Boulevard.
A river in Chincoteague, Virginia between Chincoteague Inlet to the south and Chincoteague Bay to the North.

A river in eastern Virginia, in the United States. It rises at Chester Gap, a wind gap in the Blue Ridge Mountains a few miles southeast of Front Royal, Virginia, near the single point where Warren, Fauquier, and Rappahannock counties come together. It flows southeastward, past Remington, Kelly's Ford, and Richardsville, before it is joined by the Rapidan River, its largest tributary, from the right. Then the Rappahannock passes through the city of Fredericksburg. Southeast of Fredericksburg, it begins to slow and widen into a brackish tidal estuary approximately 80 km long. It passes two small, but historic, river towns, Port Royal and Port Conway, which sit opposite each other, the former on the south bank, the latter on the north. Then it flows past Tappahannock on its southern bank, a point where the river is well over a mile wide. The last settlements of any size before reaching salt water are Irvington and White Stone Beach. The broad river enters Chesapeake Bay approximately 24 km south of the mouth of the Potomac and approximately 80 km east of the state capital, Richmond.
A river in the United States state of Virginia. Located on the Middle Peninsula, between the Rappahannock and York Rivers.
A river located in Mathews County in the Middle Peninsula region of Virginia. It flows into Mobjack Bay, which in turn, empties into the Chesapeake Bay.
A river.

A navigable estuary, approximately 64 km long, in eastern Virginia in the United States. The York River is formed at West Point, approximately 64 km east of Richmond, by the confluence of the Mattaponi and Pamunkey rivers. It drains into the Chesapeake bay towards the southeast, entering the bay approximately 8 km east of Yorktown, which sits alongs its southern shore.

An estuarine inlet of the Chesapeake Bay between the independent cities of Hampton and Poquoson in the Hampton Roads area of southeastern Virginia. The Southwest Branch begins as Newmarket Creek, a marshy, tidal creek which flows from its headwaters in Newport News into Hampton where it widens greatly and empties into the river. The Northwest Branch also begins in Newport News as Brick Kiln Creek, and is dammed along the Hampton city and York County border to form Big Bethel Reservoir. It flows from the reservoir into Poquoson, where it becomes the Northwest Branch.
A short tidal estuary which empties into Hampton Roads near its mouth.

A tidal estuary located in the independent city of Virginia Beach, Virginia, in the United States, and flows into the Chesapeake Bay west of Cape Henry at Lynnhaven Inlet, beyond which is Lynnhaven Roads.
A river. A tributary of Green Bay. It is formed in Forest County and flows southeasterly towards the bay of Green Bay, spending most of its time winding through Marinette County.

A river flowing to Lake Superior in northern Wisconsin in the United States. It issues from the southwestern end of Caroline Lake, a 51.6 ha shallow lake on the boundary of Ashland and Iron Counties which drains an area of acidic peatlands to its east. The Bad River initially flows southwestwardly before turning generally to the north for most of its course, along which it passes through the city of Mellen, Copper Falls State Park, and the community of Odanah in the Bad River Indian Reservation. In the vicinity of Mellen, the riverbed is commonly bedrock and boulder-strewn with numerous whitewater rapids; the river passes over waterfalls and through a granite gorge in Copper Falls State Park. In its lower course in the Bad River Reservation the river's delta along Lake Superior contributes to a 6400 ha complex of wetlands.

A warm freshwater stream that lies in northeastern Sauk County and southern Juneau County in central Wisconsin.
A river. A tributary of Lake Noquebay.

A river. A tributary of Lake Michigan via the Bay of Green Bay. The Oconto River is 209 miles long, stretching from its headwaters, near Wabeno, Wisconsin and empties into the Bay of Green Bay in the city of Oconto. Its drainage basin covers 2,416 square miles, encompassing most of Oconto County as well as portions of Shawano, Marinette, Menominee, Langlade, and Forest Counties.
A river draining into Green Bay.

A freshwater estuary located in northern Door County, Wisconsin. It flows in a southeasterly direction into Rowley's Bay on Lake Michigan.

A river. A tributary of Lake Michigan on the Door Peninsula in eastern Wisconsin in the United States. The Ahnapee rises in southern Door County and flows generally southeastwardly into northeastern Kewaunee County, past the village of Forestville, where it is dammed. Downstream of Forestville the river becomes a freshwater estuary of Lake Michigan and is paralleled by a rail trail. It joins Lake Michigan at the city of Algoma.

A river in east central Wisconsin that is a tributary to Lake Michigan. It merges with the East Twin River in the city of Two Rivers at its mouth with the lake. The source of the river is located in southeast Brown County, Wisconsin, where it is called Neshota River. On its course it passes through the unincorporated villages of Kingsbridge and Shoto.

A river, about 65 km long, in eastern Wisconsin in the United States. It flows into Lake Michigan at the city of Manitowoc. The Manitowoc River is formed in eastern Calumet County by its north and south branches. From the confluence of its forks, the Manitowoc flows generally eastwardly through central Manitowoc County, to its mouth at Lake Michigan in the city of Manitowoc. Its largest tributary is the Branch River.
A river that flows into Lake Michigan about 2 km north of the mouth of the Manitowoc River.
A river.

A river flowing to Lake Michigan in eastern Wisconsin in the United States. It is about 115 km long and enters the lake at the city of Sheboygan. The Sheboygan River rises in eastern Fond du Lac County and initially flows northeastwardly through northwestern Sheboygan County, southeastern Calumet County and southwestern Manitowoc County before turning southeastwardly back into Sheboygan County. Along its course the river flows past the village of Saint Cloud, the cities of Kiel and Sheboygan Falls, the village of Kohler and the city of Sheboygan, where it enters Lake Michigan. At Sheboygan Falls it collects its two largest tributaries, the Mullet River and the Onion River.
A river.

A river that flows to Lake Michigan at the city of Racine in southeastern Wisconsin in the United States. The Root River rises in the Waukesha County suburb of New Berlin and flows generally southeastwardly through the Milwaukee County suburbs of West Allis, Greenfield, Greendale and Franklin, into Racine County, where it enters Lake Michigan at Racine.
